<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUL 93 / Serb president orders release of ailing opposition leader
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SERBIAN PRESIDENT Slobodan Milosevic yesterday ordered the release of jailed
opposition leader Mr Vuk Draskovic and his wife Danica.
Mr Draskovic had been on hunger strike for eight days in protest against his
detention after a violent anti-government demonstration on June 1.
The order for the couple's release came after intense international pressure
and a warning from doctors treating Mr Draskovic in the main Belgrade
hospital that he 'could die in a matter of hours'.
While thousands gathered in Belgrade's central square to celebrate, Mr
Draskovic had to stay overnight in the Belgrade hospital where he had been
kept, too ill to be moved.
Mr Milosevic said: 'The events accompanying the legal proceedings against
Vuk Draskovic are creating a very ugly picture beneath the dignity of our
nation.' Mr Draskovic was being freed because of 'a real political and media
campaign against Serbia organised by some countries. . . .because of its
battle for freedom and equality.'
Mr Milosevic said Mrs Draskovic would also be freed in order to avoid
'humiliating' Mr Draskovic. 'The two people are extremely attached to one
another and their feelings must be respected.'
The Draskovices were arrested on June 1 after an anti-government protest in
which a policeman died and 28 people were hurt. Police severely beat the
couple while in jail. They later went to hospital, under heavy police guard,
because of the injuries.
Faced with the possibility of mass unrest if Mr Draskovic died, Mr Milosevic
issued the order for his release. However, he made clear that Mr Draskovic,
head of the Serbian Renewal party, the country's largest opposition group,
would still face assault charges against a policeman.
The order came only a few hours after the German government and US President
Bill Clinton pressed for the release of the couple from prison.
In Sarajevo, meanwhile, the first cases of typhus were reported yesterday as
the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees warned that the city was
on the 'brink of disaster'.
Bosnia radio reported an outbreak of seven cases of typhus and 700 cases of
dysentery in the shattered capital.
Bosnia's collective presidency voted against the ethnic division of Bosnia
and called for a new London conference on the war-torn republic.
Mr Thorvald Stoltenberg, the international mediator, is due to meet eight of
the 10 members of the rotating leadership today in Zagreb, the Croatian
capital.
</TEXT>
