<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Program buying and positive
data lift Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
PROGRAM buying contributed to a strong rally on Wall Street yesterday as
investors respon-ded to positive economic reports and equities continued to
recover from their recent losses, writes Karen Zagor in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed 38.75 higher at 3,514.42, after
breaking through the 3,500 level at noon. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 advanced
5.81 to 448.64 and the Nasdaq composite rose 3.92 to 702.71. New York SE
volume reached 284m shares, while rises led falls by 1,283 to 715.
Investors took heart after weekly unemployment claims showed a sharper than
expected fall. The market was also encouraged by improved same-store sales
for June from a number of large US retailers.
Woolworth, however, dipped Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 27 1/8 after warning
investors that it would post disappointing second-quarter earnings. The
retailer reported a slight decline in domestic same-store sales for June.
Sears climbed Dollars 1 7/8 to a 52-week high of Dollars 58 after unveiling
a strong improvement in comparable store sales for June. Wal-Mart moved
forward Dollars 1 to Dollars 26 1/2 and JC Penney appreciated Dollars 1 7/8
to Dollars 45 1/8 .
Nike rose Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 55 3/4 in active trading after the
athletic shoe and apparel maker predicted single-digit growth for the
current fiscal year. The company also authorised a stock buyback plan of up
to Dollars 450m in class 'B' common stock. Reebok, Nike's main rival, put on
Dollars  7/8 at Dollars 28 1/8 , while LA Gear firmed Dollars  3/8 to
Dollars 10 1/2 .
Walt Disney was finally up Dollars  1/8 at Dollars 38 3/4 after losing
ground in the morning following a delayed opening as the company's Euro
Disney operations posted disappointing earnings.
Newmont Mining lost Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 53 7/8 , after falling Dollars
3 3/8 a day earlier. Late on Wednesday a secondary offering of 9.65m common
shares in the company was priced at Dollars 54 3/4 a share through
underwriters led by Salomon Brothers.
In the technology sector, IBM held steady at Dollars 46 5/8 and
Hewlett-Packard advanced Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 78 3/4 , but Digital
Equipment edged Dollars  3/4 lower to Dollars 38 1/2 .
Airline issues rallied after Wednesday's weakness, with AMR, parent of
American Airlines, rising Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 61 7/8 and Delta Dollars
1 1/2 to Dollars 47 7/8 , but UAL eased Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 124 1/4 .
In Nasdaq trading, Microsoft rose Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 84 7/8 and Intel
climbed Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 54 3/4 .
Canada
TORONTO posted its largest one-day loss for about 33 months, led by steep
declines in gold and energy stocks.
The TSE 300 index dropped 51.9 to close at 3,920.9. Declines outnumbered
advances by 542 to 238 after volume of 70m shares valued at CDollars 795.9m.
The gold shares index fell 5.2 per cent and the energy group lost 2.97 per
cent as 12 of the 14 sub-groups lost ground. The transportation group shed
4.8 per cent, largely due to a decline in Laidlaw 'B' shares of CDollars
5/8 to CDollars 9 1/4 . The company posted a third-quarter loss, against
year-ago net earnings, and sharply lower nine-month net, although the latest
periods included a heavy charge.
</TEXT>
