<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / International Company News: Weak demand and high grape
prices hit Remy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
REMY-COINTREAU yesterday highlighted the problems of the French drinks
industry by announcing a 25 per cent fall in net profits, to FFr202m
(Dollars 35.43m), in the year to March 31, from FFr271m in the previous
year.
The group, which owns a string of famous French drink brands, ranging from
Remy-Martin cognac to Cointreau liqueur, attributed the fall in profits to
the difficulties of the champagne market, where many producers have been
badly affected by the combination of weak demand and high grape prices.
The squeeze on champagne margins was the chief cause of a reduction in
operating profits, from FFr1.05bn to FFr876m. The Cointreau brand was
affected in the first half by a change in its distribution arrangements.
However, Remy managed to maintain margins in cognac, which was buoyed by
strong growth in the fledgling Chinese market, and to improve them in
liqueurs and spirits.
Turnover fell from FFr6.47bn to FFr5.83bn in the year to March 31, but Remy
benefited from a reduction in financial costs, from FFr605m to FFr577m, over
the same period.
The news of Remy's fall in profits comes at a sensitive time for the French
drinks industry, particularly for the champagne sector.
