<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / International Company News: Advertising decline hits income
at Dow Jones
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DOW JONES &amp; CO, the publishing group which owns the Wall Street Journal,
yesterday reported a 5.3 per cent drop in second-quarter net income, which
it said was due mainly to a decline in advertising lineage at the Journal.
The company reported net income of Dollars 39.81m, or 40 cents a share,
compared with Dollars 42.02m, or 41 cents a share, in the same period of
last year. Revenues rose 4.2 per cent to Dollars 487m.
For the first half, the company reported net income of Dollars 70.75m, or 71
cents a share, up from Dollars 58.17m, or 57 cents a share, on revenues
which rose 5.2 per cent from Dollars 904m to Dollars 950m. First-half
earnings rose 2.6 per cent when a 1992 charge for changes in income tax and
post-retirement benefits is excluded.
Mr Peter Kann, chairman, said second-quarter advertising lineage had been
soft, largely because of general economic uncertainty. 'Businesses are still
cautious about a recovery and that affects their spending.'
Operating income for the quarter at the group's information services
segment, which includes the Dow Jones/Telerate and Business Information
Services groups, totalled Dollars 39.1m, up 4.4 per cent, on revenue 8.6 per
cent ahead at Dollars 214m.
The business publications segment saw a 12.3 per cent slide in operating
income, to Dollars 37.9m, with revenue little changed at Dollars 210m. The
Wall Street Journal's advertising lineage was down 7.3 per cent.
Ottaway Newspapers, a community newspapers subsidiary, saw an 11 per cent
dip in operating income, to Dollars 9.1m, while revenues rose 4.6 per cent
to Dollars 63.1m. Advertising lineage rose 1 per cent.
Chevron, the US oil group, is to sell its 71-year-old headquarters building
at 225 Bush Street in San Francisco's financial district as part of its
corporate restructuring, agencies report from San Francisco.
</TEXT>
