<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / Euro Disney warns of summer loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EURO Disney yesterday warned that it would make a loss this summer and said
it had sought financial support from Walt Disney, its US parent company,
writes Alice Rawsthorn.
Mr Philippe Bourguignon, the chairman, said Euro Disney had decided to delay
the construction of the second phase of EuroDisneyland because of its
financial difficulties.
The group's share price fell sharply after the announcement and ended the
day down FFr870 at FFr5,950, their lowest level this year. In London, the
stock closed 108p lower at 675p.
Euro Disney, which opened the theme park in April 1992, originally hoped to
be profitable from the beginning.
But after a second-half deficit last year, it is heading for heavy losses in
the current financial year. It has already announced a net loss of FFr1.08bn
for the six months to March 31.
An unexpectedly high estimate of FFr500m losses in the third quarter formed
part of yesterday's warning. The company also said it would continue in the
red in the fourth quarter. The spring-summer half contains the theme park's
busiest period.
Euro Disney said it had been affected by the European recession and by the
French franc's strength against other currencies, notably the pound and the
lira. Trips from the UK fell considerably, with the number of visitors to
EuroDisneyland falling to 310,000 in the third quarter, a 50 per cent fall
on the same period last year. The decline in foreign attendance was
countered by an increase in the number of French visitors.
The group is reassessing its plans for the second phase of EuroDisneyland,
originally expected to include a second park and golf course. Mr Bourguignon
said the group had to be 'prudent for the short term'.
In the meantime Euro Disney is trying to restructure its debt in a
refinancing deal which could include raising new capital. The rise in its
net debt from FFr18.5bn to FFr21bn in the current financial year has raised
concern about the cashflow position.
Walt Disney, which owns 49 per cent of the equity, has agreed to help
finance working capital requirements until next spring when Euro Disney
hopes to have completed its refinancing.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
