<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / Contractors offer big savings to councils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES providing services for councils under compulsory competitive
tendering are cutting their prices when the contracts are renewed, according
to figures published today in the Local Government Chronicle.
The figures contradict the common view that the companies which won
contracts on the first round had treated the exercise as a 'loss-leader'.
Eight of the first nine authorities to renegotiate contracts for refuse
collection since the scheme started in 1988 have achieved real-term price
cuts of 18.4 per cent or more.
Councils using private contractors obtained savings varying from a 30 per
cent real reduction for Runnymede district council to 18.4 per cent for
Tonbridge.
Medina district council, in the Isle of Wight, is the only authority so far
to have suffered an increase.
Three contractors - Biffa Waste, Tylers, and Cory Environmental - have so
far won contracts. Only in Cherwell, in Oxfordshire, has the council's own
direct labour force kept the contract, by accepting a reduction in price
from Pounds 1.2m in 1988 to Pounds 840,000 this year.
Direct labour organisations, which in most cases beat private sector
competitors when the contracts were first put out to tender, found the
figures alarming.
Mr Mark Bramah, principal adviser to the Association of Direct Labour
Organisations, said previous studies had suggested contract prices would
rise when retendered. He said: 'I find it surprising that they are coming in
cheaper. There may be underlying reasons in each case, such as the impact of
the recession on private sector bids. Local authorities' own resource
problems could also be affecting their specifications.'
Mr Cliff Davis-Coleman, managing director of CD-C Research, which produced
the figures, estimated that further contracts to be awarded in the next two
months would confirm that private companies were prepared to offer low
prices in order to gain substantial volume in the UK market.
Competitive tender myth challenged, Page 10
</TEXT>
