<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Since almost all soap opera leaves me stone cold, it is difficult to summon
up much concern at the passing of Eldorado which ends today (7.00 BBC1).
There seems little doubt that, had it been allowed to continue for a few
more months, it would have begun to do its intended task: hold up the
ratings on week-nights when 'EastEnders' is off. But given the present
politics of broadcasting, it needed to succeed instantly to survive, and no
soap opera has ever done that. Will Alan Yentob, now controller of BBC1 as
well as BBC2, do what his predecessor was dissuaded from and commission
Casualty as a three-times-a-week half-hour drama to replace 'Eldorado'?
Hospital drama is one of the earliest, commonest and most successful types
of soap.
In his third Reith Lecture (9.30 Radio 3), Professor Edward Said considers
intellectuals both as expatriates and as people on the margins of their own
societies, and ponders whether exile inspires their thinking. Said, himself
both an intellectual and a Palestinian who lives in the US, seems ideally
placed to judge.
</TEXT>
