<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / University teachers' union censured on election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ASSOCIATION of University Teachers will almost certainly have to rerun
the election for its general secretary's post after a finding by the
Certification Office, the official union watchdog, that the election was
improperly conducted.
Mr David Triesman, who took up his post with the 31,000-strong union in
February, beat Dr Peter Borcherds in a ballot last December by just 276
votes.
Following complaints by Dr Borcherds about the conduct of the election, an
internal AUT inquiry discovered that about 500 part-time staff working for
the Open University were probably not sent ballot papers.
Dr Borcherds' complaints were also investigated by the Certification Office,
which yesterday published its findings. It said that 'the AUT failed to
ensure, so far as was reasonably practicable, that every person entitled to
vote in that election was given the opportunity to do so', as required by
law. Two other complaints from Dr Borcherds were rejected.
The Certification Office does not have the power to take the AUT to court,
but its findings could be used to take legal action in an attempt to force
the union to rerun the ballot.
The AUT is taking legal advice but is likely to decide to pre-empt any legal
action by rerunning the ballot.
Mr John Monks, deputy general secretary of the Trades Union Congress, now
seems certain to be elected general secretary at the annual congress in
September. Nominations do not close until July 19, but Mr Monks - who would
take over from Mr Norman Willis - has already secured more than half the
nominations from unions for the post.
</TEXT>
