<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / British Coal staff cuts confirmed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COAL has confirmed that it is to shed 3,000 white-collar jobs as it
continues its struggle to reduce costs.
Mr Neil Clarke, chairman, said yesterday that the cuts were essential if
collieries that were still in operation after the recent round of closures
were to win coal sales.
Under a restructuring plan the five operational groups will be reduced to
just two, and opencast mining operations will be streamlined. The plan
includes changes to the organisation of marketing, finance, operations,
information, and technology. Many in-house services are to be outsourced.
British Coal said trade unions would be fully consulted about the
restructuring. It hopes to achieve staff reductions by voluntary redundancy
where possible.
The 3000 jobs are out of a total 5,500 under review in white-collar
departments.
British Coal hopes to put the main elements of the new structure in place by
September-October and have it complete by March-April 1994.
Mr Martin O'Neill, Labour's energy spokesman, said: 'These job losses are
the first indication of the knock-on effect of the pit closure programme and
are part of a wider acceleration of the run-down of the industry in the mad
dash for privatisation.' British Coal is seeking private operators for the
last five of the 19 collieries it no longer wants to keep open. These are
Shirebrook in Nottinghamshire, Taff Merthyr in Mid Glamorgan, Coventry,
Merseyside's Parkside and Sharlston in West Yorkshire. Advertisements will
be appearing in the national press.
</TEXT>
