FT  09 JUL 93 / Clowes theft appeal fails
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PETER CLOWES, the former financier jailed for stealing investors' funds
from his Barlow Clowes investment empire, yesterday lost his appeal against
10 convictions for theft, John Mason writes.
The Court of Appeal also rejected Mr Clowes's appeal against the length of
the 10-year sentence.
Mr Clowes' argument that he was not guilty of theft because investors had
signed a mandate giving the company absolute discretion over the handling of
their money was rejected by three judges.
Mr Clowes is considering whether to ask for leave to appeal to the House of
Lords.
An appeal against conviction by Mr Clowes's second-in-command, Dr Peter
Naylor, was also dismissed.
