<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / War hero's desk sells for Pounds 1.76m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DESK made in 1812 for the Marquess of Anglesey, a hero of the Battle of
Waterloo, sold for Pounds 1.76m at Christie's yesterday - an auction record
for English furniture.
The marquess lost a leg when he led the cavalry as second in command to the
Duke of Wellington at Waterloo.
The Regency mahogany desk is monumental in size and highly crafted with
bronze enrichments and ebony and brass inlay. It was sold by the executors
of the late Sir John Musker, and had been estimated at between Pounds
400,000 and Pounds 600,000.
Sotheby's is to hold a series of sales in October disposing of treasures
from Schloss St Emmeram, Bavaria, the family seat of the princes von Thurn
und Taxis. The sales are expected to raise about Pounds 5.6m.
</TEXT>
