<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / Revenue 'key to Nadir probe'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL ALLCOCK, the Inland Revenue investigator alleged by Mr Michael
Mates, former Northern Ireland minister, to have first blown the whistle on
Mr Asil Nadir by tipping off the Stock Exchange, has given his first
detailed account of the close links he says he cultivated with the Stock
Exchange.
He told the Financial Times that he had close contacts with the Stock
Exchange's surveillance unit for nearly 10 years, and that without the help
of the Revenue the complex transactions involving Swiss companies could not
have been penetrated.
Mr Allcock was the head of SO-2, the Revenue's crack investigative unit. In
that capacity he investigated the personal tax affairs of Mr Asil Nadir, the
former chairman of Polly Peck International, who fled to northern Cyprus to
escape trial on charges of theft and fraud. Mr Allcock was suspended on full
pay after allegations of bribery last autumn.
Mr Allcock said SO-2 had been given a loose rein by the Revenue. 'You were
expected to use your initiative . . . my specific area was the Stock
Exchange.'
According to Mr Allcock strong informal links were built up between SO-2 and
the Stock Exchange's surveillance unit specialising in insider-dealing
investigations from 1984 onwards.
'I became a very close friend with a number of individuals working for the
Stock Exchange . . . We regularly met for lunch or a beer. We took turns to
entertain each other and as a result I was given a lot of information and
documents about various individuals, brokers and transactions ranging from
multi-file share applications on government issues to share dealings in tax
haven companies'.
The Stock Exchange has indicated that the SFO's raids on Mr Nadir's offices
was based on information gathered over several years.
But Mr Allcock claims that the Stock Exchange 'for political reasons' is
trying to downplay the strong links between the two agencies.
He said how he first became involved in the Nadir case. 'The first I knew
that the Swiss companies had something to do with Nadir was when a broker
identified one of the companies as being linked to Nadir. The broker had met
Nadir's son Birol on a number of occasions.'
The information was linked to the activities of various Geneva-based
companies which SO-2 subsequently discovered to be linked to Polly Peck
share dealings.
'The Stock Exchange investigators worked with me with open arms . . . They
knew that their investigative powers were very limited . . . the
self-regulatory powers were a joke. They gave us sheets and sheets of
information on various trading transactions involving Swiss companies . . .
The Exchange built up a portfolio but never managed to get behind the
companies.'
According to Mr Allcock, SO-2 discovered that many of the transactions
linked to Mr Nadir's business empire were cleared through the bank accounts
of Turkish students working in London.
Mr Allcock emphasised that the information exchanged between SO-2 and the
Stock Exchange had 'nothing to do with Mr Nadir's personal tax affairs'.
While Mr Allcock insisted he had never passed information directly to the
SFO on the Nadir case, it is understood that there was co-operation on other
cases.
Mr Allcock confirmed that two days after the SFO raid on South Audley
Management, a property management company that handled the Nadir family's
private affairs, he and his colleague Mr Richard Cook attended a meeting at
Vizards, then Mr Nadir's solicitors.
He said he and Mr Cook had been anxious to reassure Vizards that SO-2 was
not leaking information to the SFO, as had been alleged to Mr Allcock by
Coopers &amp; Lybrand, Mr Nadir's accountants, who had threatened to cease all
further co-operation with the Revenue on identifying Mr Nadir's personal tax
affairs.
'The SFO raid was a monumental disaster from a Revenue point of view as the
publicity provoked a share price collapse and undermined attempts to get
more tax owed to us back from Mr Nadir.'
Until then SO-2 is understood to have succeeded in obtaining 'substantial
sums of corporate and personal tax owed by Nadir'.
Sources involved in the SFO raid at the time insist that large sums of
illegally obtained funds were unaccounted for by the Stock Exchange, the
Revenue, and the SFO at the time and are still unaccounted for.
During a taped interview last autumn with officials of the Board's
Investigation Office, the Revenue's disciplinary committee, Mr Allcock was
shown a copy of an agenda of a meeting to be held between himself, an Iraqi
businessman and an accountant. At the bottom of the memo were handwritten
the words 'pay off Pounds 25'.
Mr Allcock said: 'I was asked what the 'pay off' meant. I was quite hurt. I
said couldn't answer it, it had nothing to do with me . . . I have never
been offered bribes, nor have I ever sought them.'
</TEXT>
