<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: TGWU rounds on Labour reform plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS and DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR BILL MORRIS, general secretary of the Transport and General Workers'
Union, yesterday launched a strong attack on Labour's front bench as the
TGWU's biennial conference voted to reject the Labour leadership's plans for
reforms of internal party democracy.
Delegates gave Mr Morris a standing ovation as he warned those in the Labour
party who wanted to introduce the principle of one member one vote that 'we
will not be moved'. Mr Morris added: 'We are not turkeys and we are not
going to vote for Christmas.'
Meanwhile, in the Commons yesterday, some Tories taunted Mr John Smith, the
Labour leader, over the opposition to reforms he faced from the unions.
Mr Tony Newton, Leader of the House, said Mr Smith's attempts to persuade
the unions of his plans had been a 'catastrophe'.
But Mr Smith's aides said the Labour leader 'stood by every word' of the
speech he made to the TGWU conference in Bournemouth on Wednesday when he
called for the relationship between Labour and the unions to be
'modernised'.
The stage is now set for a battle on union-Labour links at this autumn's
Labour party conference.
Only the AEU engineering union and the ISTC steel union positively support
the Labour leader on the key issue of removing unions from the selection of
local candidates.
With a few other small unions probably backing the leader that might amount
to 15 per cent out of the 70 per cent of the votes allocated to the unions
at the conference.
Combined with about 65 per cent of the constituency parties - who together
account for 30 per cent of the total vote - supporters of Mr Smith's plan
for one-member-one-vote command no more than one-third of the conference
votes.
Some of the opponents of the the Labour leader's plan are seen as potential
waverers. The conference delegations from three out of the big six unions
affiliated to the party - Nupe the public service union, Usdaw the
shopworkers and MSF the white collar union - could, it is believed, be
persuaded to shift position to support one-member-one-vote.
</TEXT>
