<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Curb set on use of Lloyd's reserves
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is to amend the Finance Bill to ensure withdrawals by Lloyd's
Names from new tax-free reserves may be made only to fund losses.
Though this was always the government's intention, Labour had criticised the
original proposals for failing to set explicit restrictions on the
circumstances in which withdrawals could be made.
Labour yesterday welcomed the government's amendment - tabled ahead of
Monday's Commons report stage - saying it was exactly what it had been
arguing for.
The move followed undertakings by ministers in committee stage to
incorporate the suggested change if a 'legitimate' way could be found of
doing so.
The arrangements set out in the Budget do nothing to help Names on the
troubled insurance market who have already been hit by heavy losses. But
they will allow them to establish tax-free reserves against heavy losses
they may incur in the future.
Under the new arrangements - which come into in effect to cover the 1992
underwriting year - Names will be able to transfer up to 50 per cent of
profits to the new reserve each year, provided the value of the funds in the
reserve does not exceed 50 per cent of the Name's overall premium income
limit.
Amounts withdrawn will be made to fund losses or cash calls. Withdrawals not
used to meet losses will attract tax.
</TEXT>
