<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: MPs urge move on Maxwell funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPS FROM both sides of the House of Commons last night urged the government
to ensure that leading City institutions which undertook commissions for the
late Robert Maxwell contributed to the restoration of the pension funds he
plundered.
Mr Frank Field (Lab Birkenhead), chairman of the Commons social security
committee, suggested appropriate sums paid on a voluntary basis might enable
some 'grand City institutions' to avoid having their reputations fatally
flawed in legal pro-ceedings.
He was strongly supported by Mr David Shaw (C Dover), another member of the
committee, who envisaged the largest contribution being in the region of
Pounds 100m.
Mr Shaw argued that directors and other individuals associated with Maxwell
companies who had been paid large sums to remain silent should be asked for
smaller contributions of around Pounds 50,000.
He was particularly critical of the investment bank Goldman Sachs, claiming
that the company must have known that Maxwell was a desperate man involved
in strange deals.
Both Mr Field and Mr Shaw praised the government for the action it had taken
to mitigate the hardship suffered by the members of Maxwell pension funds
but insisted that tax-payers should not be asked to shoulder the burden of
restitution.
</TEXT>
