<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Senior Tories call for more oil tax
concessions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR TORY backbenchers are putting the government under renewed pressure
to make further concessions over its proposed changes to North Sea oil
taxes.
Six Conservative MPs last night tabled a group of amendments calling for a
three-year transition period before the changes take full effect.
The amendments may be considered when the Finance Bill returns to the
Commons for its report stage next Monday.
The move followed a 90-minute meeting at the Treasury involving three of the
MPs, industry representatives and Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to
the Treasury.
One of the backbenchers - Mr John Butterfill, Conservative MP for
Bournemouth West - said that Mr Dorrell had listened to the group's
arguments very carefully.
Treasury officials said last night that the new proposals would be
considered but that the government was unlikely to allow further
concessions.
The additional amendments were welcomed by members of the oil industry last
night. One large North Sea oil company said the new terms would encourage
more sustained activity during the transition to the new tax regime.
The renewed initiative comes less than a month after the government bowed to
pressure by agreeing to extend some short-term help to companies worst
affected by the changes, by making it easier for them to claim the Pounds
200m earmarked in the Budget for this purpose.
The amendment committed the government to allowing companies to claim up to
Pounds 10m each until the end of next year for exploration work affected by
the abolition of tax relief.
Under the Budget changes, the rate of petroleum revenue tax (PRT) paid on
existing fields would be reduced from 75 per cent to 50 per cent, while
relief for exploration work would be abolished.
Mr John Watts, Tory MP for Slough, said last night: 'If we had a three-year
transition period as we have proposed, we could maintain a higher level of
activity in the North Sea, the rundown of activity would be more orderly and
there would be less loss of jobs.'
</TEXT>
