<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Lilley seeks broad debate on rise
in social security spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN and MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOCIAL SECURITY spending is set to increase 19 per cent in real terms by
2000 even if unemployment falls by a quarter, according to projections
released yesterday by Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary.
The projections are included in a compendium of statistics published by Mr
Lilley to stimulate debate on the growth of social security spending, which
last year cost Pounds 74bn.
The publication of the figures immediately led Mr John Smith, the Labour
leader, to accuse ministers of 'softening up' the public for big social
security budget reductions.
The Labour leader highlighted remarks made in Tokyo on Wednesday by the
prime minister, that the UK, with other Group of Seven nations, would have
to take unpopular but necessary steps to keep social security budgets in
check.
As Mr Lilley is fond of pointing out, however, the Labour party has itself
recognised the need for a detailed review of the social security budget in
setting up its own social justice commission.
Mr Lilley said yesterday: 'We need an informed public debate on the reform
of social security to ensure that it becomes a better, more focused system
which protects the most needy and vulnerable in our society without
outstripping the nation's ability to pay.'
If there were no fall in unemployment between now and the end of the century
the social security bill would reach Pounds 93m by 2000. The proportion of
GDP it would swallow would rise from 12.3 per cent to 13.5 per cent.
However, economic growth would do much to reduce the scale of the problem.
If unemployment fell by a quarter the social security bill would rise to
Pounds 88bn, a real increase of 2.6 per cent a year. If unemployment were
halved social security spending would fall as a percentage of GDP.
A third of the increase in social security in the next seven years will come
from sickness, invalidity and disability benefits. A quarter will come from
housing benefit and a fifth from payments to one-parent families.
Most of the rest comes from the build-up of state earnings related pensions.
Steps have been proposed to curb the growth of invalidity benefit by
imposing tougher medical tests. A cross-departmental review led by the
Downing Street policy unit is examining housing benefit as part of a review
of housing policy.
Mr Lilley expressed contentment yesterday over the emerging debate on the
increase in one-parent families. While there are no plans to cut their
benefits, he believes that a debate could help in changing attitudes which
have encouraged the increase.
However, Mr Smith's attack in the Commons yesterday gave notice of the
opposition's intention to harry the government on the social security issue
in the weeks running up to the Christchurch by-election on July 29.
Conservative MPs fear that a Labour onslaught intended to show pensions are
under threat could prove electorally damaging in what already promises to be
a hard-fought contest.
Short-term political considerations could make it difficult for Mr Lilley to
launch the long-term debate he wants.
The growth of social security. HMSO. Pounds 9.50.
</TEXT>
