<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / Howard rejects criticism of police authority reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL authorities did not have a 'monopoly of knowledge' on the way the
police service should be run, Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, said
yesterday.
Mr Howard faced several interruptions as he defended government proposals
for small, more businesslike police authorities to senior police officers
and local authority leaders at the Association of Chief Police Officers'
conference in Birmingham.
Farmers, head teachers and shopkeepers all knew something about crime, Mr
Howard said. Some had been victims of it and all understood the fear of it.
Such people should be able to bring their knowledge to police authorities.
The government, as part of a wide-ranging agenda for police reform, intends
to reduce local authority representation on police authorities, with the
home secretary appointing some members and authority chairs directly. Chief
constables as well as local authorities have attacked the proposals, which
were published in a white paper last month.
Mr Robin Wendt, secretary of the Association of County Councils, told the
conference that the white paper made no attempt to assess the benefits of
different structures and merely asserted that the new system would be
better. 'As a basis for major constitutional change, that simply will not
do,' he said.
Mr John Burrow, chief constable of Essex and president of ACPO, warned Mr
Howard that if he did not allow a genuine dialogue on proposed changes to
the police service 'you run the risk of not taking the main players with
you'.
There appears little likelihood of the government changing its mind over the
reform of police authorities, which mirror changes elsewhere in the public
sector. But Mr Howard told the conference that he had no pre-determined
position on another aspect of the reforms - the Sheehy report on police pay
and responsibilities - although he believed that 'if we can improve the link
between performance and pay we will all be better off'.
He said he would consider responses to the report until September and hoped
to move forward in consultation with the police service.
