<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / Scots council reform confirmed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday confirmed that it is to sweep away Scotland's
two-tier local government structure and replace it with a system of
single-tier authorities.
Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary, said that 25 unitary authorities were to be
created in place of the nine regions and 53 districts of mainland Scotland.
The three unitary island councils would be unchanged.
Mr Lang was given a noisy reception when he announced his white paper in the
House of Commons and several opposition Scottish MPs walked out. By the end
of the question and answer session following his statement, Mr Lang was left
addressing a virtually deserted chamber. The greatest impact was achieved by
Labour which left en masse in a carefully stage-managed publicity stunt.
On the controversial question of the possible privatisation of Scotland's
water and sewerage services Mr Lang said he planned to create three 'public
water authorities' to own and operate 'the current water and sewerage
assets'. The new authorities would 'arrange for new investment in ways which
will maximise the involvement of the private sector'. Mr Lang said he would
consult with interested bodies before producing detailed proposals for
legislation.
The new map of local authorities - to be known simply as councils - is
exactly the same as that leaked to The Scotsman newspaper late last week
which provoked fury among the opposition.
Strathclyde region, which includes nearly half the Scottish population, will
disappear and be broken up into 10 councils. The four Scottish cities,
Edinburgh, Glasgow, Aberdeen and Dundee, will become unitary authorities.
Lothian, Tayside, Grampian and Central regions will be broken up. The whole
of the Highlands, consisting of a region and eight districts, will become a
single council. Stirlingshire is among former counties which will reappear.
The new councils will not be of uniform size.
The number of police forces and fire brigades is to remain at eight, but
joint committees of councils will be set up where they cover more than one
area. There will be no joint committees in fields such as education or
social work.
Legislation to create the councils will be introduced in the next session of
parliament. Elections will be held in May 1995 and the new councils will
come into existence in May 1996. There will be elections every three years.
Mr Lang said that savings of about Pounds 200m over five years could be
expected from the new structure. Transitional costs depended on the new
authorities but were estimated at between Pounds 120m and Pounds 196m.
Mr Tom Clarke, the shadow Scottish secretary, called the proposals 'the Tory
revenge on the Scottish people and on Scottish local government'. Sir David
Steel, for the Liberal Democrats, called them 'the most corrupt proposals
that have been presented to the House by any government in my time in the
House'.
Mr Robert Gould and Mrs Jean McFadden, the Labour leaders of Strathclyde
Regional Council and Glasgow District Council respectively, called the
proposals 'an act of political vandalism'.
</TEXT>
