<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / Council contractors reduce tendering prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPULSORY competitive tendering has brought fresh savings for councils  -
with bidders cutting their prices when the contracts are renewed, according
to figures published today in the Local Government Chronicle.
The figures contradict the common view that the companies which won
contracts on the first round had treated the exercise as a 'loss-leader'.
Seven of the first eight authorities to renegotiate deals with outside
contractors for refuse collection since the scheme started in 1988 have
achieved real-term price cuts of 18.4 per cent or more.
Councils using private contractors obtained savings varying from a 30 per
cent real reduction for Runnymede district council to 18.4 per cent for
Tonbridge.
Medina district council, in the Isle of Wight, is the only authority so far
to have suffered an increase.
Three contractors - Biffa Waste, Tylers, and Cory Environmental - have so
far won contracts. In Cherwell, in Oxfordshire, the council's own direct
labour force emerged as the lowest bidder with a price Pounds 360,500 lower
than 1988's Pounds 1.2m.
Direct labour organisations, which in most cases beat private sector
competitors when the contracts were first put out to tender, found the
figures alarming.
Mr Mark Bramah, principal adviser to the Association of Direct Labour
Organisations, said previous studies had suggested contract prices would
rise when retendered. He said: 'I find it surprising that they are coming in
cheaper. There may be underlying reasons in each case, such as the impact of
the recession on private sector bids. Local authorities' own resource
problems could also be affecting their specifications.'
Mr Cliff Davis-Coleman, managing director of CDC Research, which produced
the figures, estimated that further contracts to be awarded in the next two
months would confirm that private companies were prepared to offer low
prices in order to gain substantial volume in the UK market.
Dr Stefan Szymanski of the London Business School yesterday told a seminar
on tendering organised by CDC Research, that competitive tendering had
already delivered substantial reductions before the contracts came up for
renewal.
Figures produced independently by Dr Szymanski, which compare the
expenditure on refuse collection declared by 217 local authorities in
England and Wales in 1988 with the amount they paid for contracts, show the
average cost saving is 27 per cent, with a variation in savings from 42 per
cent to 5 per cent.
Dr Szymanski said the cost savings could come from three sources -
efficiency gains, poorer terms and conditions for the labour force, and
reduced quality. However, recent research by the Audit Commission, the local
government spending watchdog, suggested that quality had not been adversely
affected. This led Dr Szymanski to suggest that the savings had come from
the workforce - not generally in lower wages, but in longer working hours
and reduced benefits - and from improved efficiency.
Dr Szymanski's findings are questioned by the Institute of Local Government
Studies at Birmingham University, which, on the basis of a smaller sample of
authorities, believes accrued savings are about 8 per cent since 1988.
