<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / PIA plan attacked by Pru chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICK Newmarch, chief executive of Prudential, Britain's largest life
insurer, said the company would be an 'unwilling' participant in a proposed
new self-regulating body if a current blueprint it was considering is
adopted.
He told the Financial Times Conference on Retail Regulation that a report by
Sir Brian Jenkins, commissioned by the board of the proposed Personal
Investment Authority, far exceeded the remit of a self-regulating body.
Mr Newmarch renewed his call for direct statutory regulation of the
financial services industry and abolition of the self-regulating framework.
He called for a structure similar to that used to regulate building
societies. Regulators needed certain powers now prohibited to them, such as
the ability to ban the sale of inherently flawed products.
After the conference, he said he doubted the PIA would come to fruition and
the Prudential would not participate unless the majority of industry
participants joined on a voluntary basis.
Separately, Mr Andrew Large, chairman of the Securities and Investments
Board, told the conference he had established a joint working party on
disclosure with Fimbra and Lautro, the two self-regulating bodies for retail
financial services.
The working party will consider, among other things, recommendations from
the Office of Fair Trading on disclosure as well as a proposal from Mr Tim
Miller, an SIB consultant, to help consumers understand the costs of the
products they buy.
Mr Large said it was evident the disclosure regime for life insurance
products proposed by the SIB did not go far enough in meeting consumers'
desire for more information.
