<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / PIA plan attacked by Pru chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICK Newmarch, chief executive of Prudential, Britain's largest life
insurer, said the company would be an 'unwilling' participant in a proposed
new self-regulating body if a current blueprint it was considering is
adopted.
Mr Mick Newmarch, chief executive of Prudential, said that a report
commissioned by the board of the proposed new Personal Investment Authority
and carried out by Sir Brian Jenkins far exceeded the remit of a
self-regulating body.
Speaking at the Financial Times Conference on Retail Regulation, Mr Newmarch
renewed his call for direct statutory regulation of the financial services
industry and abolition of the self-regulating framework.
He urged the adoption of a structure similar to that used to regulate
Britain's building societies, saying that regulators needed certain powers
now prohibited to them such as the ability to ban the sale of inherently
flawed products.
After the conference, Mr Newmarch said he doubted that the new PIA would
come to fruition and that the Prudential would not participate unless the
majority of industry participants joined on a voluntary basis.
Separately, Mr Andrew Large, chairman of the Securities and Investments
Board, told the conference he had established a joint working party on
disclosure with Fimbra and Lautro, the two self-regulating bodies for retail
financial services.
The working party will consider, among other things, recommendations from
the Office of Fair Trading on disclosure as well as a proposal from an SIB
consultant, Mr Tim Miller, to help consumers better understand the costs of
the products they buy.
Mr Large said it had become evident that the disclosure regime for life
insurance products proposed by the SIB last year did not go far enough in
meeting consumers' desire for more information.
'But simply calling for more information is not the answer,' he said.
Mr Large added that he did not intend to approve the PIA as a
self-regulating body unless it met the tough new standards in raising
investor protection he set out in a letter to the PIA board earlier this
year.
</TEXT>
