<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / Romiti investigated over party political financing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR CESARE ROMITI, chief executive of the Fiat group, is being formally
investigated by Turin magistrates for alleged illicit financing of political
parties. He was interrogated for three hours on Wednesday.
Mr Romiti was placed on the list of people under investigation for alleged
illicit party financing by Milan magistrates at the end of May but has yet
to be interrogated by them. Earlier he had offered the full co-operation of
Fiat in the matter.
The Turin action relates to separate episodes. The magistrates' move follows
statements by two prominent local Socialists, Mr Giusy La Ganga, an MP for
the city, and Mr Beppe Garesio, a former editor of Avanti], the Socialist
party's daily newspaper.
The two claim discussions were held in Fiat's Turin headquarters on three
occasions between 1988 and 1990 about how the group should help fund the
Socialists.
Mr Romiti is understood to have denied any discussion of funding the party
and said the conversations focused on political and cultural matters.
Mr La Ganga has been served with seven separate notices from Turin
magistrates that he is under investigation for alleged corruption, and a
further two from Milan magistrates. Mr Garesio has already received three
separate notices.
Last week, Mr Giovanni Agnelli, Fiat chairman, admitted at the annual
meeting that the group had paid a previously undeclared L50bn (Pounds 19m)
in kick-backs to politicians over the previous 10 years. Mr Francesco
Susini, director-general of the Culture Ministry and for more than a decade
the most influential official in the Italian arts world, was yesterday
arrested on charges of corruption and abuse of office.
His arrest coincided with the arrest of Mr Fernando Pinto on charges of
masterminding the October 1991 fire that severely damaged the Bari opera
house of which he was the director.
