<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 93 / Hungary devalues forint
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HUNGARY yesterday devalued the forint by 3 per cent and raised a key
interest rate by 3 percentage points.
The currency is linked to a basket divided equally between the dollar and
the Ecu, and the central bank passed off the devaluation as a 'technical
step' in response to the dollar's rise against European currencies.
This devaluation follows one of 1.9 per cent last month, adding to
speculation that the exchange rate policy is softening. Pressure for a
fundamental shift has been growing as Hungarian exports have fallen and the
external trade balance deteriorated.
Exports in the first four months were down 27.2 per cent compared with a
year earlier, depressed by recession in Hungary's main markets of Germany
and Austria.
The current account deficit amounted to Dollars 423m (Pounds 282m) for the
first two months, leading some analysts to estimate that the shortfall for
the year could be as high as Dollars 2bn, about 8 per cent of gross domestic
product.
The central bank is financing the deficit with a record spree on
international capital markets. Yesterday it announced two more bond issues -
a five-year Y50bn (Pounds 307m) bond in Tokyo and a Pounds 100m bond in
London. The bank's borrowings so far this year total Dollars 2.7bn.
Recent bond issues have sold relatively well, despite the external balance
deterioration.
</TEXT>
